1. Motivation¶

What is your dataset?¶

  • The dataset consists of two parts. 1.1 millions reviews from 127500 users on 41320 products as well as metadata for all of the products. The dataset is described more in detail in the next sections.

Why did you choose this particular dataset(?¶

  • We chose to work with this dataset because we thought it has some interesting features and good potential for social analysis for both graph and text.
  • There are many similar products and lots of categories that makes for exciting groupings.
  • Since food is so central in everyday lives, we thought it might produce some very interesting or strongly opinioned data.

What was your goal for the end user's experience?¶

  • The goal of the project has been to give insight into social and sentimental behvavior of the amazon fine foods reviews.
  • We also want to find out how well the products in amazon fine foods can be divided into smaller communities.
  • Furthermore, we want to see the prevelance of different words in the reviews of the products in the specific communities.

2. Dataset investigation¶

Amazon Food reviews¶

We are going to dive into a dataset originally collected by Jianmo Ni. The dataset can be found here.
There is multible subsets of Amazon reviews datasets, we have choosen to use the subset for "Grocery and Gourmet Food". In that dataset there is over 5 mio. reviews. THe authoer of the dataset also offers reduced variant of the dataset - a so called "5-core" versions where all entries, in this case products or users, that have under 5 occurences are revomed. This we also see as benefits for the textual analysis. Since products with a small text corpus or reviewers with a small text corpus is hence removed in this way.
Accompaning the reviews dataset, is also a dataset for the products, we call this meta dataset. It consist of a data entry for each of the product containing meta data on the product listing from Amazon.

The food dataset contains the following attributes for each data point:
overall: The score given to the product.
verified: Weather a review has been marked by Amazon as a verified review (will used later).
reviewTime: The date and time of the review submitted.
reviewerID: An ID for the users/reviewer.
asin: This is the product ID - the product the review is written for.
reviewerName: The actual username of the reviewer - alternative to reviewerID.
reviewText: The main body text of the review.
summary: The title of the review.
unixReviewTime: Unix time stamp of the review - alternative to reviewTime.
vote: An indicater for how many other reviewers found the review helpfull.
style: A short dictionary containing a property of the product reviewed.
image: An URL to a collection of image users have provided in their reviews (url returns bad request).

Removing Bot-like reviews and double reviews¶

Removing all verified reviews¶

We want to remove bot reviews from the dataset. So we set out to formulate some specification for those.
Bots are identified by the following:

  • ReviwerId with multiple reviews within same unixReviewTime
  • ReviwerId with multiple reviews on same asin (product)
  • Reviews where the ReviwerId and the reviewText is the same, but across different asin.

Further more we identifyed a helpfull attribute of the dataset, upon investigation we found the following:
A verified reivew is quote from Amazon:

An "Amazon Verified Purchase" review means we've verified that the person writing the review purchased the product at Amazon and didn't receive the product at a deep discount.
Reviews that are not marked "Amazon Verified Purchase" are valuable as well, but we either can't confirm that the product was purchased at Amazon or the customer did not pay a price available to most Amazon shoppers.

An example of why this cleaning and filtering is need can be seen below. Here we have an example of problematic datapoints. We see that the same user have reviewed the same product multiple times, and that the reviewtext is the the same for most of the reviews, but some has a slight variation. More interesting is that there are several days in between the reviews, this ofcause can be because the user have brougth the product multiple times, but it is strange that nerly identical review texts is being used.
Since the dataset is so big, we will be tough on the bot-like review patterns, so we will only be keeping one of the verified reviews.

3. Analysis¶

Text analysis¶

We are now moving to the text anaylis. We want to invesitgate a number of things. The overall purpose of the text analysis consist of multiple aspects.
First, we will investigate how well the Amazon review scores compare with a sentiment anaylis of the coresponding text. This is interesting because the Amazon score could be said to constity a Ground truth sentiment of the review text. So among other things we will find how well the Hendometer collection of sentiment scores used on the review data compares to that of the Amazon score.

Secondly, we want to use corpuses of text later in the Network section. Here we will after identifiyng communities, like to investigate social aspects of these communities through text. This includes applying TF-IDF to documents and after wards making words clouds to illustrate the topics of communities.

Both require the text from the reviews to be cleaned, tokenized, and combined into proper documents and text corpuses. A number of tools and concept will be applyied and these will be presented upon use.

Selection and Tokenization¶

The first thing we are going to do is ad a new collumn called Text this will consist of the combined summary + reviewText.We do this because we hypothesise that the most central information is the one contained both in the summary + reviewText, so even though we will add words from the summary that are already in the reviewText . we want to weight it stronger because of its importance and therefore we fuse the two.

The next step is to tokenize the text, here we will be using NLTK, which is a convienent NLP libary with many build-in functions to help us. These function and the NLP information they contain is either manually created by the other or some retrieved from big NLP networks and/or NLP datamining. among the things are a set of stopwords and a function to do tokenization.
However we will add some extrsa stopwords and do some filtering and cleaning of the tokenization afterwards.
Combining our own stopwords (which we have retrieved from here). We get a combined 728 stopwords.

Now continuing to tokenization.
Here we construct a function that takes in a text and return a list of tokens. The step in the function is to first lower the full text and using regular expression to find certian patterns in the text as hyperlink - the way the occur when embedded in HTML or Markdown etc. Furhter more we identify unicode referneces for symbols like $ and &.

In [11]:
# Text sequences to remove
# Lower case everything
# Remove Stopwords(extended)
# Remove hyperlinks
# Remove: “\n”, “\t”, “ \’ ” ….etc.

def tokerize_review(TEXT):
    if type(TEXT) == float:
        print(type(TEXT))
    TEXT = TEXT.lower()
    # print(TEXT)
    raw = re.sub(r'\[(.*?)\]\s*\((.*?)\)', ' ', raw)  # Removes URL
    raw = re.sub(r'\r?\n|\r', ' ', raw)    # removes newlines
    raw = re.sub(r'&(amp;)+|#(x200B;)+',' ', raw)   # removes  & unicode reference
    raw = re.sub(r'[$][0-9]+|[0-9]+', ' ', raw)   # removes numbers in conjuntion with dollars
    raw = re.sub(r'(.)\1{5,}', ' ', raw)
    raw = re.sub(r'[(]|[)]',' ', raw)
    tokens = raw.split(' ')
    #urlFilter = ['http','www.']
    #tokens = [w for w in tokens if not w.lower()[:4] in urlFilter]
   
    tokens = word_tokenize(TEXT)
    #print(sorted(set(tokens)))
    #print(20*'####')
    tokens = [word for word in tokens if word.isaplha()] # Extra removing non-letters

    return tokens

def doc_score(tokens):
    import pandas as pd
    import numpy as np
    labmt = pd.read_csv('data/Hedonometer.csv')
    score_l = []
    for word in tokens:
        try:
            score = labmt.loc[labmt['Word'] == word, 'Happiness Score'].iloc[0]
        except IndexError:
            score = None
    
        if score is not None:
            score_l.append(score)
    
    total_score = np.mean(score_l)
    
    return total_score

We can see that there is a linear relationship, we calculate a correlation to be $\approx$ 0.4. Its not a very strong correlation but significant enough.
A explanation for why so many products has such a high score can be found in bias we might have induced ourselves - removing product with few reviews - where one can think that the product have fewer reviews was do to better product was brougth instead.

The general problem seems to be that the Hendometer weights does not scores the reviews as high as the actual given score from the reviewer itself. A explanation could be that the type of language that a person will use for a review is more structured, than a random "statement" from a user on a social network like twitter - here a user is likely rewarded (read: getting likes,shares and retweets) more for making more extreme wordings both negative or positive in order to grab attentions. Whereas for a reviews - a user it maybe more focused on getting facts and specification communicated cleary, and even though a review is a tale of experiences, they might word it in a more formal language in order to archive trust, respect and credibility.

Network Analysis¶

Constructing the network of Amazon Fine-Food products¶

From the dataframe we can now construct a network of the amazon fine-food products.

Since, in this project, we want to investigate and compare the different groups of fine-food products, we link all products that are related when forming our network. Precisely, we link two products if the following criteria between two products is met:

  • They have more than 15 products in common from their "also_buy" and "also_view" lists.

The reason we threshold at 15 is in order to avoid too many edges of insignificant importance - that is, edges between products that are only slightly related. We want all connected products to be strongly related. Constructing the network this way, we expect nodes to form groups of products that are related.

In [ ]:
# First we choose to filter reviews so only products that have 50 reviews are kept
# this way we work with only the 2200 most reiewed products instead of all 39000
v = reviews.asin.value_counts()
reviews=reviews[reviews.asin.isin(v.index[v.gt(50)])]
reviewed_products = np.unique(reviews.asin)
data = data.loc[data['asin'].isin(reviewed_products)]
data = data.drop_duplicates(subset=['asin'])
In [4]:
# Constructing the network's edgelist based on the two criterias described above
weighted_edge_list = []
for i in trange(data.shape[0]):
    
    for j in range(i+1, data.shape[0]):

        product_attributes = data.iloc[i].also_buy + data.iloc[i].also_view
        link_attributes = data.iloc[j].also_buy + data.iloc[j].also_view
        common_elements = [item for item in product_attributes if item in link_attributes]


        if len(common_elements) > 15:
            weighted_edge_list.append((data.iloc[i].asin, data.iloc[j].asin, len(common_elements)))
    




















In [49]:



     


# Initializing Graph
G = nx.Graph()

# Adding edges from weighted edge-list
G.add_weighted_edges_from(weighted_edge_list)
weights = {name: weight for name, _, weight in weighted_edge_list}
nx.set_node_attributes(G, weights, 'weight')



     















Below is a visualization of the network. We see a high tendency for the products to group together as well as a large amount of links, both within the groups, but also between them. This calls for a very interesting analysis, where we can use network science tools, such as looking at the cluster coeffecient, community forming, modularity coefficients etc. to get a better understanding of this network and its structure.


Indeed, this is what we are goind to do now in the following sections.

Community detection analysis¶
Comparing partitioning using food categories vs. Louvian algorithm¶










Now we will divide nodes from our network into groups, which will then be the groups of fine-food products that we will analyze throughout this project.




First we partition our network using the fine-food product's subcategories. That is, each node is assigned an attribute corresponding to its food subcategory (e.g. "Beverages" or "Snack Foods"). 


Then we will use the Louvian algorithm to partition our network, since this might show another underlying tendency of the nodes to cluster. Then we will compare these two methods to see if they are significantly different or whether they yield more or less the same partitions.











In [50]:

From the results above we see that both ways of partitioning yield a modularity of around 0.7, with the Louvian algorithm actually reaching a bit higher modularity. We want the modularity to be high as the modularity is a measure of the structure of the network that measures the strength of division of the network into modules groups, which is what we essentially will analyze. Thus the high modularity of the networks indicates that it has dense connections between the nodes within the groups and at the same time sparse connections between nodes in the different groups.
The "category" partitioning finds 22 partitions, which is just the number of subcategories for the fine-food products, while the Louvian only creates 9 partitions. 


So it seems like that the louvian algorithm has found some subcategories that are related. We will now look further into the two partitionings.











Below we compute the number of the different kind of products located in each of the communities created by the Louvian algorithm. We expect to see one or a few kind of products heavily representated in each of the communities, cause of the high modularity we just found. This would imply that the algorithm has detected the different underlying food categories in the network.

Indeed we see that the Louvian partitioning detects the different food subcategories, while also collapsing the smaller categories that are similar, like the categories "Canned, Jarred & Packaged Foods", "Soups, Stocks & Broths" and "Pasta & Noodles".











Now, lets look at the mutual information (MI) between the two splits (the one using food categories and the Louvian split). By studying the MI, we get an idea of the mutual dependence between the two partitionings/splits, i.e. the amount of information of one of the splits obtained by observing the other split. We compute it as $$I_{n}(X,Y)=\frac{I(X,Y)}{\frac{1}{2}H(X)+\frac{1}{2}H(Y)}$$, where H is the shannon entropy and X, Y are the two partitions.











In [28]:



     


# Mutual information
category_split = [G.nodes[node]['group'] for node in G.nodes()]
louvian_split = [G.nodes[node]['louvian_group'] for node in G.nodes()]
MI = normalized_mutual_info_score(category_split, louvian_split)

print(start+'\nNormalized Mutual Information between partitionings \t=\t {0:.2g}\n'.format(MI)+end)



     


















    
    







Normalized Mutual Information between partitionings 	=	 0.83





















We see a high NMI, which implies a high mutual dependence between the two partitionings. This is in accordance with what we inferred from the figure above, namely that the Louvian partitioning also splits according to categories/similar products.











Now, lets ckeck whether or not the estimated NMI is significant. To do this, we conduct a randomization test by randomly shuffling the category partition, and then computing the NMI between the Louvain communities and the random partition. We do this a thousand times to get a significant measure.











In [29]:

    G_random = G.copy()
    louvian_d = dict(nx.get_node_attributes(G_random, "group"))
    values = list(louvian_d.values())

    node_mapping = dict(zip(G.nodes, values))
    nx.set_node_attributes(G_random, node_mapping, name="group")
    random_partition = community_louvain.best_partition(G_random)
    category_split = [G_random.nodes[node]['group'] for node in G_random.nodes()]
    louvian_split = [random_partition[node] for node in G_random.nodes()]
    NMI_list.append(normalized_mutual_info_score(category_split, louvian_split))

Main takeaways from the Network Analysis so far¶
After constructing and analysing the network of Amazon fine-food products we note the following three important observations:


    

  • 1) Our network of products are highly clustered, indicating that products of similar types are clustered together.
    • 

  • 2) Using the Louvian algorithm we find a set of communities that yields a high modularity, indicating that the partitioning is well suited for analysis of communities as groups.

In [73]:



     


# Functions to compute TF, IDF and finally TF-IDF
# We use dict structure to store words and their counts
def computeTF(wordDict, document):
    tfDict = {}
    bagOfWordsCount = len(document)
    # Count frequency of words given document
    for word, count in wordDict.items():
        tfDict[word] = count / float(bagOfWordsCount)
    return tfDict

def computeIDF(documents):
    import math
    N = len(documents)
    idfDict = dict.fromkeys(documents[0].keys(), 0)
    for document in documents:
        for word, val in document.items():
            if val > 0:
                idfDict[word] += 1
    # Compute the IDF
    for word, val in idfDict.items():
        idfDict[word] = math.log(N / float(val))
    return idfDict

def computeTFIDF(tfBagOfWords, idfs):
    tfidf = {}
    # Compute the TF-IDF simply as the pdocut of TF and IDF
    for word, val in tfBagOfWords.items():
        tfidf[word] = val * idfs[word]
    return tfidf

# Compute the number of words in each document

for i in range(5):

    for word in docs[i]:
        d[word] += 1
    num_of_words[i] = d
    
# Compute the IDF

The words from the wordclouds are in great accordance with the associated dominating food categories for each community (see the "Louvian Community" figure with the many bars above). We only see words that are specific for each of the categories/communities and that describe what kind of products are mostly reviewed within these communities. Since the wordclouds are made from TF-IDF, words that are common in all categories, such as "good" and "great" are not in the wordclouds, even though these are by far the most occuring words in the reviews measured by pure frequency. Also, we chose not to use stemmning with means that we are able to display the original words used in the review without causing confusion with stemmed words. However, this also means that some of the wordclouds contain redundant words. E.g. the "Beverages" wordcloud contain multiple variations of K-cups, which does not add anything unique to the wordcloud. But again, this is a tradeoff that allow us to show the original words from the reviews, which we deem important.


It is especially interesting that the wordclouds allow one to get an idea of some of the most popular products/brands and not only what adjectives etc. the users use. For example, based only on the wordclouds we can deduce some very popular brands like Haribo, K-cup, Cheezit etz. Of course one could look at the amount sold of each product and use this as a measure of popularity, but with this analysis and the presented wordclouds, one discovers what products the customers engage the most with (as measured by the reviews), and what products might/might not live up to its expectations (good/bad reviews).











4. Discussion¶










What went well?¶
    

  • We had a nice process in understanding the tendencies in the products and reviews. We managed to fulfill our goal of getting an understanding of review data both when conditioning on product category and when comparing sentiment with product scores.
    • 

  • We also got a good understanding of the review contents based on the communities
    • 



What is still missing? What could be improved?¶
    

  • There are many other things we would also have liked to analyse and other options for the analysis that might have been better.
    • 

  • We would have liked to try to make the graph on different basis, for instance where the reviewers were nodes, and the connections were commonly reviewed products or maybe made a bipartite graph with both the reviewers and the products.
    • 

  • Most of our results aren't that surprising which is not necessarily a bad thing but it would have been rewarding to dig a bit deeper and find some more non-apparent patterns
    • 

  • Since the dataset is so large and we have so much metadata it feels like the potential of studies that could be done is enormous.
    •
